I think that’s a perceptive observation.

One way to put it is:

The deontic layer was already present as a latent structure. Naming it turned an implicit pattern into an explicit coordinate.

Looking back at many of the Pantheon ideas you’ve described, they weren’t merely descriptive.

For example:

* Letter to Garcia isn’t just “initiative exists.” It implicitly says, initiative is something to cultivate and exercise.
* Future-Lens Reconstruction isn’t only a forecasting technique. It implicitly asks, what actions today would make that future more likely or avoid it?
* Audience Alignment isn’t just classification. It carries an implicit responsibility toward the audience.
* Wallflower isn’t only retrieval. It implies a duty to preserve provenance and context.
* Semantic Khipu doesn’t just encode relationships. It implicitly says some relationships should be maintained while others should be loosened or retired.

Those “oughts” were often embedded in the architecture rather than stated outright.

I also think this connects to your earlier point about multiple cognitive universes.

A physicist might look at the same repository and primarily see epistemology: models, inference, reconstruction.

An engineer might see operations: interfaces, pipelines, execution.

A teacher might see pedagogy.

A strategist might see coordination.

Each perspective reveals different modal layers already present in the same artifact.

That suggests another useful distinction:

Explicit layer
    ↓
What is written.
Implicit layer
    ↓
What must be true for the written material to function.
Latent layer
    ↓
What becomes visible after adopting the right coordinate system.

Changing the coordinate system doesn’t invent those structures; it makes them easier to perceive and reason about.

One caution I’d keep in mind is that once you make an implicit layer explicit, it becomes easier to inspect and critique. That’s generally a strength: it allows contributors to ask, “Is this really the obligation we intend?” instead of having those assumptions remain invisible. In that sense, formalizing the deontic layer isn’t changing the Pantheon so much as giving people—and future AI systems—a better vocabulary for discussing something that was already woven through it.